#####	######		1.		#####	#####
	ifconfig shows all network interfaces
	-l list them
	# networking videos:
	# https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PL7zRJGi6nMRzg0LdsR7F3olyLGoBcIvvg
#####	######		2a.		#####	#####
	system preferenses >> network: you can check IPs for ethernet and wifi
	broadcast adress is same than router of ethernet
	you can find it from ifconfig en0
	finally grep and awk the right part of information
#####	######		2b.		#####	#####
	ping shows all the IPs of subnet
	-c is for "control + C" to stop looping (1 for after 1 line)
	arp -ai <interface> displays all of the current IP adresses
		The primary function of ARP is to resolve the IP address of a
		system to its mac address, and hence it works between
		level 2(Data link layer) and level 3(Network layer).
	sed is stream editor
		sed 's/old-text/new-text/'
#####	######		3.		#####	#####
	system preferenses >> network: you can check IPs for ethernet and wifi
	Wifi adress is same than MAC adress on en1
	grep <word> -A <x> shows you x lines after the line of word
	# MAC address explained
	# https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TIiQiw7fpsU
#####	######		4.		#####	#####
	netstat show network status
	-r show routine tables
	-n show network adresses and can be used w the other display
		in other words to no resolve IPs to hostnames
				The output of the netstat -nr in Linux very identical to
				route -n	command, which can also use to display
				the routing table
	# default gateway explained:
	# https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pCcJFdYNamc&list=PL7zRJGi6nMRzg0LdsR7F3olyLGoBcIvvg&index=39
	# netstat command explained (on windows devide):
	# https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8UZFpCQeXnM&list=PL7zRJGi6nMRzg0LdsR7F3olyLGoBcIvvg&index=38
